    {
      "text": "In a German main clause, the verb always comes in the second position — no matter what comes first. The first position can be the subject, a time word, a place phrase, or almost anything else. But the verb must be second.",
      "title": "The verb is always in second position"
    },
    {
      "text": "In English, when you move something like 'yesterday' or 'every day' to the front of a sentence, the subject still comes right after it: 'Yesterday, I saw him.' In German, moving that element to the front pushes the subject after the verb instead. So if the first position is taken by something other than the subject, the subject and verb swap order — this is called inversion. For example: 'Gestern sah ich ihn.' The verb stays second, and the subject shifts to third.",
      "title": "Inversion: subject and verb swap when something else comes first"
    }
  ],
